03959nam a22005295i 9780300206609DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002066097 a10.12987/97803002066092doi  a(DE-B1597)485893  a(OCoLC)882258680  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aREL0670402bisacsh04a232.922231 aDavis, Stephen J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChrist Child :bCultural Memories of a Young Jesus /cStephen J. Davis. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSynkrisis00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart One: Methods and Approaches -- t1. Cultural Memories of a Young Jesus -- t2. Texts and Readers -- tPart Two: Graeco-Roman Sites of Memory -- t3. Bird-Watching -- t4. Cursing -- t5. Learning Letters -- tPart Three: Christian-Jewish-Muslim Encounters -- t6. Jews and Christians -- t7. Muslims and Christians -- tEpilogue: Reimagining a Young Jesus -- tAppendix A: The Greek Paidika -- tAppendix B: The Arabic Gospel of the Infancy, Chapters 36– 53 -- tAppendix C: Jesus and the Birds in St. Martin’s Church, Zillis, Switzerland -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tEditions, Collections, Objects, and Translations -- tSecondary Literature -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLittle is known about the early childhood of Jesus Christ. But in the decades after his death, stories began circulating about his origins. One collection of such tales was the so-called Infancy Gospel of Thomas, known in antiquity as the Paidika or “Childhood Deeds” of Jesus. In it, Jesus not only performs miracles while at play (such as turning clay birds into live sparrows) but also gets enmeshed in a series of interpersonal conflicts and curses to death children and teachers who rub him the wrong way. How would early readers have made sense of this young Jesus? In this highly innovative book, Stephen Davis draws on current theories about how human communities construe the past to answer this question. He explores how ancient readers would have used texts, images, places, and other key reference points from their own social world to understand the Christ child’s curious actions. He then shows how the figure of a young Jesus was later picked up and exploited in the context of medieval Jewish-Christian and Christian-Muslim encounters. Challenging many scholarly assumptions, Davis adds a crucial dimension to the story of how Christian history was created.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Christology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030014945640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030020660940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300206609423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300206609/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY